%%TITLE
Influence of chronic illnesses and underlying risk conditions on the incidence of pneumococcal pneumonia in older adults.
%%ABSTRACT
Objective To investigate hospitalizations from pneumo- coccal pneumonia in older adults with specific underlying chronic conditions, evaluating the influence of these condi- tions in developing pneumonia.
Methods Population-based cohort study involving 27,204 individuals 60 years old in Southern Catalonia, Spain. All cases of hospitalization from pneumococcal pneumo- nia (bacteremic and nonbacteremic) were collected since 01/12/2008 until 30/11/2011. Cox regression was used to calculate hazards ratio (HR) and estimate the association between baseline conditions and the risk of developing pneumococcal pneumonia.
Results Maximum incidences (per 1000 person-years) appeared among patients with history of prior pneumonia (14.6), nursing home residents (12.8), persons with immu- nodeficiency/asplenia (7.7) and patients with chronic pul- monary disease (7.6). In multivariable analysis, age (HR: 1.05), nursing home residence (HR: 4.59), history of prior pneumonia (HR: 3.58), stroke (HR: 2.50), chronic heart disease (HR: 1.53), chronic pulmonary disease (HR: 4.09), diabetes mellitus (HR: 1.66), smoking (HR: 1.69) and immunosuppressive medication (HR: 1.87) appeared sig- nificantly associated with an increased risk of pneumococ- cal pneumonia.
Conclusion Our data support that nursing home resi- dence, chronic pulmonary disease and immunocompromis- ing conditions are the underlying conditions most strongly associated with an increasing risk of pneumococcal pneu- monia in older adults. This data underline the need for bet- ter prevention strategies among these persons.
Keywords Incidence · Pneumococcal pneumonia · Risk factors · Streptococcus pneumoniae
%%PATIENTS AND METHODS
Design and study population
This is a closed population-based prospective cohort study including 27,204 individuals 60 years or older assigned to nine primary care centers (PCCs) in Tarragona (a mixed residential–industrial urban region on the Mediterranean coast of Southern Catalonia, Spain), who were prospec- tively followed from a 36-month consecutive period. The study was approved by the ethical committee of the Catalo- nian Health Institute (CEIC IDIAP “Jordi Gol” no. P09/49) and was conducted in accordance with the general princi- ples for observational studies set out by the institution. We note that, in the study region, there is a publicly funded antipneumococcal vaccination program recommending the 23 valent pneumococcal vaccine for high-risk and older adults (>60 years) since 2002, with a vaccine uptake reach- ing approximately fifty percent among the general elderly people [].
Cohort members were followed from when the study started (December 1, 2008) until the occurrence of a first episode of pneumonia, the enrollment from the PCC ceased, death, or until the end of the study (November 30, 2011). Mean temperatures in the study area for sum- mer and winter seasons throughout the study period were 24.9 °C (76.9 °F) and 10.2 °C (50.4 °F), respectively [].
Data sources
The electronic clinical record system of each participating PCC, coded according to the International Classification of Diseases 10th Revision (ICD-10), was used to identify the presence of chronic illnesses/underlying conditions and to establish baseline characteristics of the cohort at study start []. The hospital discharge diagnosis databases, coded according to the International Classification of Diseases, 9th Revision, Clinical modification (ICD-9), were used to identify presumptive pneumococcal pneumonia (ICD-9: 481) and all-cause pneumonia cases (ICD-9: 480–486). In addition, the specific microbiological registries of reference laboratories were also used to identify cases of pneumococ- cal infections not detected in ICD-9 codes. All presumptive cases were further reviewed by two trained physician inves- tigators who checked the hospital medical records, only being definitively included if on conclusion of the medical record review, the diagnosis was verified according to crite- ria mentioned below.
Conventional diagnostic workup included blood cul- ture, sputum culture and S. Pneumoniae urinary antigen test (Binax-NOW) [], which were performed as indicated by the attending physician in each case. The isolates of S. pneumoniae were identified from blood and sputum sam- ples by standard methods in the microbiology laboratory of the two hospitals in the study area (Joan XXIII and Santa Tecla).
Outcomes
Primary endpoints were hospitalization from pneumonia and death from any cause. Pneumonia was defined as an acute respiratory illness, with evidence of the presence of a new infiltrate on a chest radiograph. Aspirative pneumonias and nosocomial pneumonias (i.e., symp- toms occurring more than 48 h after hospital admission) were excluded [].
Bacteremic pneumococcal pneumonia was considered when Streptococcus pneumoniae was isolated from blood specimens or other sterile sites. Nonbacteremic pneumo- coccal pneumonia was considered when the patients had a typical clinical syndrome of pneumonia without bacte- remia (negative or not performed blood culture), but they had a sputum culture that yielded pneumococci with no other likely bacterial pathogens and/or they had positive Binax-NOW Streptococcus pneumoniae urinary antigen test [].
Death from pneumonia (case fatality) was considered when the patient died (in-hospital or not) within the first 30 days after the diagnosis [].
Covariates
Main baseline covariates were the presence of any of the following ten chronic illnesses or underlying conditions (which have been related with increasing risk of IPD): chronic pulmonary disease (including chronic bronchitis, emphysema or asthma), chronic heart disease (including congestive heart failure, hypertensive heart disease, cardio- myopathy, valvulopathy, cardiac dilatation or ventricular hypertrophy), chronic liver disease(including chronic viral hepatitis, alcoholic hepatitis or cirrhosis), chronic nephrop- athy (including nephrotic syndrome, renal failure, dialysis or transplantation), diabetes mellitus, smoking, alcoholism, immunodeficiency (including AIDS and anatomic or func- tional asplenia), cancer (including solid organ or hema- tological neoplasia) and immunosuppressive medication (20 mg/day of prednisone or equivalent). Other baseline covariates were age, sex, nursing home residence, history of hospitalization for pneumonia in previous 5 years, his- tory of coronary artery disease (myocardial infarction or angina), history of stroke and dementia.
Statistical analyses
Incidence rates were calculated as person-years, consider- ing the denominator the sum of the persons-time contrib- uted to each individual during the study period. Case fatal- ity rates were calculated by dividing the number of cases of deaths from pneumonia by the absolute number of cases in each age- and sex- specific stratum. Event rates were based on the first episode of pneumonia occurring during the study period and they do not include multiple events per person. Confidence intervals (CI) were used to compare incidence and mortality rates between the different catego- ries and population groups. Chi-squared and Fisher’s tests were used to calculate p values in the comparison of pro- portions, whereas Student’s test and one-way analysis of variance were used to compare continuous variables.
Multivariable Cox regression analysis was used to cal- culate hazards ratio (HRs) and estimate the association between baseline conditions and the time to first outcome during the study period. We checked for confounders, interactions and multicollinearity among the independent variables. The final model was adjusted by all significant variables, as well as confounders and other baseline covari- ables judged of clinical importance. We assessed the pro- portional hazards assumptions adding the covariate by time interactions to the model and plot the scaled and smoothed Schoenfeld residuals []. Statistical significance was set at p < 0.05. The analyses were performed using Stata/SE ver- sion 9.1 (Stata Corp.).
